<DOC><DOCNO> AP880325-0079 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 1057EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-SatelliteLaunch     03-25 0120</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Satellite Launch,110</SECOND><HEAD>NASA Launching Scientific Satellite from Italian Site off Kenya</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   NASA, in conjunction with the Italian and WestGerman space agencies, arranged to launch a highly advancedscientific satellite today from a site off the coast of Africa, anagency spokesman said.   The satellite, carrying five payloads, was to be launched fromthe Italian-owned San Marco platform off the coast of Kenya, saidspokesman Duane Brown. Three of the payloads are American, one isItalian and the other is German, he said.   The 521-pound spacecraft will be launched with an American Scoutrocket. Its mission is to study the earth's atmosphere, Brown said.   The launch was postponed from last week because of mechanicalproblems.</TEXT></DOC>